ammy.com/grammys/artists/winona-ryder|title= Winona Ruder - Artist|website= Grammys.com|accessdate= April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===[[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!| Year\n!| Nominated work\n!| Category\n!| Result\n!| Ref. \n|-\n| [[2nd Screen Actors Guild Awards|1995]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Best Performance by a Cast]]\n| ''[[How to Make an American Quilt]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=6|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000213/awards?ref_=nm_awd|title= Winona Ryder - Awards|website= Internet Movie Database|accessdate= April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[17th Screen Actors Guild Awards|2010]]\n|''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie|Best Actress in a Miniseries or Movie]]\n| ''[[When Love Is Not Enough: The Lois Wilson Story|When Love Is Not Enough]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[24th Screen Actors Guild Awards|2016]]\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Drama Series|Best Actress in a Drama]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Stranger Things]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series|Best Ensemble in a Drama]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[25th Screen Actors Guild Awards|2017]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q101797|c=category:Winona Ryder|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no|q=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|213}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Amg name|62446|Winona Ryder}}\n* [http://www.tv.com/people/winona-ryder/ Winona Ryder] at [[TV.com]]\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|winona_ryder|Winona Ryder}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Winona Ryder|Awards for Winona Ryder]]\n|list =\n{{GoldenGlobeBestSuppActressMotionPicture 1981\u20132000}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ryder, Winona}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Actresses from California]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of theft]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Petaluma, California]]\n[[Category:People from Winona, Minnesota]]\n", "name_user": "49.184.4.208", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winona_Ryder"}
{"title_page": "LIHKG", "text_new": "{{short description|Hong Kong online forum website}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = LIHKG\n| logo = LIHKG logo.png\n| logo_size = 80px\n| url = {{Official url}}\n| commercial = Shanghai clique\n| type = {{ubl|[[Online forum]]|[[Social news]]}}\n| registration = Optional<ref group=notes>LIHKG can be viewed without an account but registration with an e-mail address registered with an ISP or a higher education institution in Hong Kong is required to submit, comment or vote.</ref>\n| language = [[Chinese language|Chinese]]\n| alexa = {{increase}}&nbsp;[https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/lihkg.com 17] {{small|{{nowrap|(Hong Kong, July 2019)}}}}\n| current_status = Active\n| area_served = Hong Kong\n}}\n{{Chinese|t=\u6284\u767b|s=\u6284\u767b|j=lin4 dang1|y=L\u00echnd\u0101ng|p=Li\u00e1nd\u0113ng}}\n'''LIHKG''' ({{zh|c=|s=|t=\u6284\u767b|p=|cy=L\u00echnd\u0101ng}}) is a multi-category [[Internet forum|forum]] website based in [[Hong Kong]]. The website has gained popularity since the launch in 2016, and is often referred to as the Hong Kong version of [[Reddit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theindependent.sg/hong-kong-university-teaching-assistant-gets-suspended-after-threatening-to-fail-student-protestors/|title=Hong Kong university teaching assistant gets suspended after threatening to fail student protestors|last=Otsuka|first=Hana|website=The Independent Singapore|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/despite-political-party-ban-hong-kong-independence-groups-persist|title=Despite Political Party Ban, Hong Kong Independence Groups Persist|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hong Kong protests: How the city\u2019s Reddit-like forum LIHKG has become the leading platform for organising demonstrations |url=https://www.todayonline.com/world/hong-kong-protests-how-citys-reddit-forum-lihkg-has-become-leading-platform-organising |work=TODAYonline}}</ref>\n\nThreads with more up-votes and replies appear towards the top of topic sections and, if they receive sufficient votes and replies, ultimately on the site's \"Popular\" section.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/realtime/finance/20161129/55980247|title=\u3010\u53cd\u65b9\u4e08\u9738\u6b0a\u3011\u9ad8\u767b\u4ed4\u68c4\u9ad8\u767b\uff01\u53e6\u8d77\u7210\u7076LIHKG \u767b\u4e0b\u8f09\u699c\u9996|website=Apple Daily \u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LIHKG pig mascot immortalized at \u9999\u6e2f\u306e\u4e0d\u81ea\u7531\u5c55 exhibition in Tokyo.jpg|thumb|LIHKG pig mascot featured at an exhibition in Japan]]\nThe website is well known for being one of the main platforms for discussing the strategies for the leaderless [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|anti-extradition bill protests]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-hong-kong-youth-activism-decentralized-protests-20190614-story.html|title=A new kind of Hong Kong activism emerges as protesters mobilize without any leaders|last=Su|first=Alice|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3016573/hong-kong-reddit-how-leaderless-extradition-protests-took|title=\u2018Hong Kong Reddit\u2019: how social media shaped extradition protests|date=29 June 2019|work=South China Morning Post|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Registration ==\nRegistration of membership is restricted to people with a [[Hong Kong]] [[ISP]] or an institution of higher education email address located in Hong Kong. Registered members may create threads on the site, while uploading contents such as text posts, hyperlinks or images. The posts then receive replies and may be voted up or down by other members. Posts are separated into various categories and are then grouped in the \"Chat\" category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/realtime/finance/20161129/55981480|title=\u9ad8\u767b\u4ed4\u53e6\u8d77\u7210\u7076 \u50b3\u300c\u65b9\u4e08\u300d\u88ab\u7092 \u6797\u7956\u821c\uff1a\u6211\u5c79\u7acb\u4e0d\u5012\uff01|website=Apple Daily \u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=What is LIHKG and how did it become go-to forum for Hong Kong\u2019s protesters? |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/society/article/3021224/hong-kong-protests-how-citys-reddit-forum-lihkg-has-become |work=South China Morning Post |date=3 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Attacks ==\n{{As of|2019|12}}, the LIHKG website was the subject of a [[distributed denial-of-service attack|DDoS attack]] by the [[Great Cannon of China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cybersecurity.att.com/blogs/labs-research/the-great-cannon-has-been-deployed-again|title=The \"Great Cannon\" has been deployed again|last=Doman|first=Chris|date=2019-12-04|website=AT&T Cybersecurty blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hong Kong Discuss Forum]]\n* [[HKGolden]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|zh}}\n\n[[Category:Internet forums in Hong Kong]]\n\n\n{{Internet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hong Kong online forum website}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = LIHKG\n| logo = LIHKG logo.png\n| logo_size = 80px\n| url = {{Official url}}\n| commercial = No\n| type = {{ubl|[[Online forum]]|[[Social news]]}}\n| registration = Optional<ref group=notes>LIHKG can be viewed without an account but registration with an e-mail address registered with an ISP or a higher education institution in Hong Kong is required to submit, comment or vote.</ref>\n| language = [[Chinese language|Chinese]]\n| alexa = {{increase}}&nbsp;[https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/lihkg.com 17] {{small|{{nowrap|(Hong Kong, July 2019)}}}}\n| current_status = Active\n| area_served = Hong Kong\n}}\n{{Chinese|t=\u9023\u767b|s=\u8fde\u767b|j=lin4 dang1|y=L\u00echnd\u0101ng|p=Li\u00e1nd\u0113ng}}\n'''LIHKG''' ({{zh|c=|s=|t=\u9023\u767b|p=|cy=L\u00echnd\u0101ng}}) is a multi-category [[Internet forum|forum]] website based in [[Hong Kong]]. The website has gained popularity since the launch in 2016, and is often referred to as the Hong Kong version of [[Reddit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theindependent.sg/hong-kong-university-teaching-assistant-gets-suspended-after-threatening-to-fail-student-protestors/|title=Hong Kong university teaching assistant gets suspended after threatening to fail student protestors|last=Otsuka|first=Hana|website=The Independent Singapore|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/despite-political-party-ban-hong-kong-independence-groups-persist|title=Despite Political Party Ban, Hong Kong Independence Groups Persist|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hong Kong protests: How the city\u2019s Reddit-like forum LIHKG has become the leading platform for organising demonstrations |url=https://www.todayonline.com/world/hong-kong-protests-how-citys-reddit-forum-lihkg-has-become-leading-platform-organising |work=TODAYonline}}</ref>\n\nThreads with more up-votes and replies appear towards the top of topic sections and, if they receive sufficient votes and replies, ultimately on the site's \"Popular\" section.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/realtime/finance/20161129/55980247|title=\u3010\u53cd\u65b9\u4e08\u9738\u6b0a\u3011\u9ad8\u767b\u4ed4\u68c4\u9ad8\u767b\uff01\u53e6\u8d77\u7210\u7076LIHKG \u767b\u4e0b\u8f09\u699c\u9996|website=Apple Daily \u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LIHKG pig mascot immortalized at \u9999\u6e2f\u306e\u4e0d\u81ea\u7531\u5c55 exhibition in Tokyo.jpg|thumb|LIHKG pig mascot featured at an exhibition in Japan]]\nThe website is well known for being one of the main platforms for discussing the strategies for the leaderless [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|anti-extradition bill protests]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-hong-kong-youth-activism-decentralized-protests-20190614-story.html|title=A new kind of Hong Kong activism emerges as protesters mobilize without any leaders|last=Su|first=Alice|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3016573/hong-kong-reddit-how-leaderless-extradition-protests-took|title=\u2018Hong Kong Reddit\u2019: how social media shaped extradition protests|date=29 June 2019|work=South China Morning Post|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Registration ==\nRegistration of membership is restricted to people with a [[Hong Kong]] [[ISP]] or an institution of higher education email address located in Hong Kong. Registered members may create threads on the site, while uploading contents such as text posts, hyperlinks or images. The posts then receive replies and may be voted up or down by other members. Posts are separated into various categories and are then grouped in the \"Chat\" category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/realtime/finance/20161129/55981480|title=\u9ad8\u767b\u4ed4\u53e6\u8d77\u7210\u7076 \u50b3\u300c\u65b9\u4e08\u300d\u88ab\u7092 \u6797\u7956\u821c\uff1a\u6211\u5c79\u7acb\u4e0d\u5012\uff01|website=Apple Daily \u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=What is LIHKG and how did it become go-to forum for Hong Kong\u2019s protesters? |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/society/article/3021224/hong-kong-protests-how-citys-reddit-forum-lihkg-has-become |work=South China Morning Post |date=3 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Attacks ==\n{{As of|2019|12}}, the LIHKG website was the subject of a [[distributed denial-of-service attack|DDoS attack]] by the [[Great Cannon of China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cybersecurity.att.com/blogs/labs-research/the-great-cannon-has-been-deployed-again|title=The \"Great Cannon\" has been deployed again|last=Doman|first=Chris|date=2019-12-04|website=AT&T Cybersecurty blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Hong Kong Discuss Forum]]\n* [[HKGolden]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|zh}}\n\n[[Category:Internet forums in Hong Kong]]\n\n\n{{Internet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "210.0.147.106", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LIHKG"}
{"title_page": "Single-player video game", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game that permits only one player}}\n{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2019}}\nA '''single-player video game''' is a [[video game]] where input from only one player is expected throughout the course of the gaming session. A single-player game is usually a game that can only be played by one person, while \"single-player mode\" is usually a [[game mode]] designed to be played by a single-player, though the game also contains multi-player modes.<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = Oosterhu | last2 = Feireiss | first2 = Lukas  | title = The Architecture Co-laboratory: Game Set and Match II : on Computer Games, Advanced Geometries, and Digital Technologies | publisher = Delft University of Technology | location = Delft | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tXBdOoZ-faYC&pg=RA2-PA108&dq=single+player+simulations#PRA2-PA108,M1 | date = March 2006 | page = 180 | isbn = 9789059730366}}</ref>\n\nMost modern [[console game]]s and [[arcade game]]s are designed so that they can be played by a single player; although many of these games have modes that allow two or more players tGTAo play (not necessarily simultaneously), very few actually require more than one player for the game to be played. The ''[[Unreal Tournament]]'' series is one example of such.<ref>\"Unreal Tournament 3 Single-player Campaign Preview.\" Unreal Tournament 3 Single-player Campaign Pr. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe earliest video games, such as ''[[Tennis for Two]]'' (1958), ''[[Spacewar!]]'' (1962), and ''[[Pong]]'' (1972), were symmetrical games designed to be played by two players. Single-player games gained popularity only after this, with early titles such as ''[[Tomohiro Nishikado#Speed Race|Speed Race]]'' (1974)<ref>\"Speed Race.\" (Game). N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref> and ''[[Space Invaders]]'' (1978).\n\nThe reason for this, according to [[Raph Koster]], is down to a combination of several factors: increasingly sophisticated computers and interfaces that enabled [[asymmetric warfare|asymmetric]] gameplay, [[cooperative gameplay]] and story delivery within a gaming framework, coupled with the fact that the majority of early games players had introverted personality types (according to the [[Myers-Briggs Type Indicator|Myers-Briggs personality type indicator]]).<ref name='RaphKoster'>{{cite web | url = http://www.raphkoster.com/2006/02/10/are-single-player-games-doomed | title = Are single-player games doomed? | accessdate = 2013-02-25 | last = Koster | first = Raph | authorlink = Raph Koster | date = 10 Feb 2006 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130208222638/http://www.raphkoster.com/2006/02/10/are-single-player-games-doomed | archivedate = 8 Feb 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough most modern games incorporate a single-player element either as the core or as one of several game modes, single-player gaming is currently viewed by the [[video game industry]] as peripheral to the future of gaming, with [[Electronic Arts]] vice president [[Frank Gibeau]] stating in 2012 that he had not approved one game to be developed as a single-player experience.<ref name='CVG'>{{cite news | title = Is single-player gaming under-threat? | date = 28 Oct 2012 | publisher = [[Future plc]] | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/374796/features/is-single-player-gaming-under-threat/ | work = Computer and Video Games | accessdate = 2013-02-25}}</ref>\n\nThe question of the financial viability of single-player [[AAA (video gaming)|AAA]] games was raised following the closure of [[Visceral Games]] by [[Electronic Arts]] (EA) in October 2017. Visceral had been a studio that established itself on a strong narrative single-player focus with ''[[Dead Space (series)|Dead Space]]'', and had been working on a single-player, linear narrative ''[[Star Wars]]'' game at the time of the closure; EA announced following this that they would be taking the game in a different direction, specifically \"a broader experience that allows for more variety and player agency\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-17-ea-has-shut-down-visceral-games | title = EA has shut down Visceral Games | first = Matt | last= Wales | date = October 17, 2017 | accessdate = October 17, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> Many commentators felt that EA made the change as they did not have confidence that a studio with an AAA-scale budget could produce a viable single-player game based on the popular ''Star Wars'' franchise. Alongside this, as well as relatively poor sales of games in the year prior that were principally AAA single-player games (''[[Resident Evil 7]]'', ''[[Prey (2017 video game)|Prey]]'', ''[[Dishonored 2]]'', and ''[[Deus Ex: Mankind Divided]]'') against financially successful multiplayer games and those offer a games-as-a-service model (''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]'', ''[[Destiny 2]]'', and ''[[Star Wars Battlefront II (2017 video game)|Star Wars Battlefront 2]]''), were indicators to many that the single-player model for AAA was waning.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2017/10/18/16491188/ea-star-wars-visceral-games-single-player  |title = EA\u2019s Star Wars \u2018pivot\u2019 is a vote of no confidence in single-player games | first =Samit | last = Sarkar | date = October 18, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/307836/Does_Viscerals_closure_prove_AAA_singleplayer_games_are_dying.php | title = Does Visceral's closure prove AAA single-player games are dying? | author = Staff | date = October 19, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/59dn78/todays-star-wars-news-makes-the-future-of-single-player-look-very-messy | title = Today's Star Wars News Makes the Future of Single-Player Look Very Messy | first=  Patrick |last= Klepek |date = October 17, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] }}</ref><ref name=\"usgamer history\">{{cite web | url = http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-rise-and-fall-of-visceral-games|  title = The Rise and Fall of Visceral Games | first = Caty | last = McCarthy | date = October 19, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work  = [[US Gamer]] }}</ref> Manveer Heir, who had left EA after finishing his gameplay design work for ''[[Mass Effect Andromeda]]'', acknowledged that the culture within EA was against the development of single-player games, and with Visceral's closure, \"that the linear single-player triple-A game at EA is dead for the time being\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-23-manveer-heir-bioware-mass-effect-ea-monetisation | title = \"I've seen people literally spend $15,000 on Mass Effect multiplayer cards\" | first = Robert | last = Purchase | date = October 23, 2017 | accessdate = October 23, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> [[Bethesda Softworks|Bethesda]] in December 7, 2017, decided to collaborate with [[Lynda Carter]] to launch a Public Safety Announcement to save single-player gaming.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/bethesda-kicks-off-a-save-player-1-sale-for-its-single-player-games/ | title = \"Bethesda kicks off a 'Save Player 1' sale for its single-player games\" | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = December 7, 2017 | accessdate = December 14, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref>\n\n==Game elements==\nAs the narrative and conflict in single-player gameplay is created by a computer rather than a human opponent, single-player games are able to deliver certain gaming experiences that are typically absent - or de-emphasised - in multiplayer games.<ref>\"ThomasDaPsycho.\" : Video Game Story Elements. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref>\n\n===Story===\nSingle-player games rely more heavily on compelling stories to draw the player into the experience and to create a sense of investment. Humans are unpredictable, so human players - allies or enemies - cannot be relied upon to carry a narrative in a particular direction, and so multiplayer games tend not to focus heavily on a linear narrative. By contrast, many single-player games are built around a compelling story.<ref>\"Tales of the Rampant Coyote: What Makes a Great RPG - Mechanics.\" Tales of the Rampant Coyote. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref>\n\n===Characters===\nWhile a multi-player game relies upon human-human interaction for its conflict, and often for its sense of camaraderie, a single-player game must build these things artificially. As such, single-player games require deeper characterisation of their [[non-player character]]s in order to create connections between the player and the sympathetic characters and to develop deeper antipathy towards the game's [[antagonist|antagonist(s)]]. This is typically true of [[Role-playing video game|role-playing games]] (RPGs), such as ''[[Dragon Quest]]'' and the ''[[Final Fantasy]]'' series, which are primarily character-driven.\n\n===Exceptions===\nThese game elements are not firm, fixed rules; single-player [[Puzzle video game|puzzle games]] such as ''[[Tetris]]'' or [[racing game]]s focus squarely on gameplay.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Massively multiplayer online game]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last1=Fullerton|first1=Tracy|authorlink1=Tracy Fullerton|title=Game Design Workshop: A Playcentric Approach to Creating Innovative Games|date=2014|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=1498785875|edition=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7xjYCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover|accessdate=30 January 2018}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Mitra|first1=Ananda|title=Digital Games: Computers at Play|date=2010|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|isbn=0816067864|pages=24\u201339|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CZrCdZE1WLQC&pg=PA24|accessdate=30 January 2018}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Perron|first1=Bernard|last2=Wolf|first2=Mark J.P.|title=The Routledge Companion to Video Game Studies|date=2014|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=1136290508|pages=253\u2013256|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P43HBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT253|accessdate=30 January 2018}}\n\n{{video game gameplay}}\n\n[[Category:Video game gameplay]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games| ]]\n[[Category:Video game terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game that permits only one player}}\n{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2019}}\nA '''single-player video game''' is a [[video game]] where input from only one player is expected throughout the course of the gaming session. A single-player game is usually a game that can only be played by one person, while \"single-player mode\" is usually a [[game mode]] designed to be played by a single-player, though the game also contains multi-player modes.<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = Oosterhu | last2 = Feireiss | first2 = Lukas  | title = The Architecture Co-laboratory: Game Set and Match II : on Computer Games, Advanced Geometries, and Digital Technologies | publisher = Delft University of Technology | location = Delft | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tXBdOoZ-faYC&pg=RA2-PA108&dq=single+player+simulations#PRA2-PA108,M1 | date = March 2006 | page = 180 | isbn = 9789059730366}}</ref>\n\nMost modern [[console game]]s and [[arcade game]]s are designed so that they can be played by a single player; although many of these games have modes that allow two or more players to play (not necessarily simultaneously), very few actually require more than one player for the game to be played. The ''[[Unreal Tournament]]'' series is one example of such.<ref>\"Unreal Tournament 3 Single-player Campaign Preview.\" Unreal Tournament 3 Single-player Campaign Pr. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe earliest video games, such as ''[[Tennis for Two]]'' (1958), ''[[Spacewar!]]'' (1962), and ''[[Pong]]'' (1972), were symmetrical games designed to be played by two players. Single-player games gained popularity only after this, with early titles such as ''[[Tomohiro Nishikado#Speed Race|Speed Race]]'' (1974)<ref>\"Speed Race.\" (Game). N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref> and ''[[Space Invaders]]'' (1978).\n\nThe reason for this, according to [[Raph Koster]], is down to a combination of several factors: increasingly sophisticated computers and interfaces that enabled [[asymmetric warfare|asymmetric]] gameplay, [[cooperative gameplay]] and story delivery within a gaming framework, coupled with the fact that the majority of early games players had introverted personality types (according to the [[Myers-Briggs Type Indicator|Myers-Briggs personality type indicator]]).<ref name='RaphKoster'>{{cite web | url = http://www.raphkoster.com/2006/02/10/are-single-player-games-doomed | title = Are single-player games doomed? | accessdate = 2013-02-25 | last = Koster | first = Raph | authorlink = Raph Koster | date = 10 Feb 2006 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130208222638/http://www.raphkoster.com/2006/02/10/are-single-player-games-doomed | archivedate = 8 Feb 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough most modern games incorporate a single-player element either as the core or as one of several game modes, single-player gaming is currently viewed by the [[video game industry]] as peripheral to the future of gaming, with [[Electronic Arts]] vice president [[Frank Gibeau]] stating in 2012 that he had not approved one game to be developed as a single-player experience.<ref name='CVG'>{{cite news | title = Is single-player gaming under-threat? | date = 28 Oct 2012 | publisher = [[Future plc]] | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/374796/features/is-single-player-gaming-under-threat/ | work = Computer and Video Games | accessdate = 2013-02-25}}</ref>\n\nThe question of the financial viability of single-player [[AAA (video gaming)|AAA]] games was raised following the closure of [[Visceral Games]] by [[Electronic Arts]] (EA) in October 2017. Visceral had been a studio that established itself on a strong narrative single-player focus with ''[[Dead Space (series)|Dead Space]]'', and had been working on a single-player, linear narrative ''[[Star Wars]]'' game at the time of the closure; EA announced following this that they would be taking the game in a different direction, specifically \"a broader experience that allows for more variety and player agency\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-17-ea-has-shut-down-visceral-games | title = EA has shut down Visceral Games | first = Matt | last= Wales | date = October 17, 2017 | accessdate = October 17, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> Many commentators felt that EA made the change as they did not have confidence that a studio with an AAA-scale budget could produce a viable single-player game based on the popular ''Star Wars'' franchise. Alongside this, as well as relatively poor sales of games in the year prior that were principally AAA single-player games (''[[Resident Evil 7]]'', ''[[Prey (2017 video game)|Prey]]'', ''[[Dishonored 2]]'', and ''[[Deus Ex: Mankind Divided]]'') against financially successful multiplayer games and those offer a games-as-a-service model (''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]'', ''[[Destiny 2]]'', and ''[[Star Wars Battlefront II (2017 video game)|Star Wars Battlefront 2]]''), were indicators to many that the single-player model for AAA was waning.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2017/10/18/16491188/ea-star-wars-visceral-games-single-player  |title = EA\u2019s Star Wars \u2018pivot\u2019 is a vote of no confidence in single-player games | first =Samit | last = Sarkar | date = October 18, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/307836/Does_Viscerals_closure_prove_AAA_singleplayer_games_are_dying.php | title = Does Visceral's closure prove AAA single-player games are dying? | author = Staff | date = October 19, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/59dn78/todays-star-wars-news-makes-the-future-of-single-player-look-very-messy | title = Today's Star Wars News Makes the Future of Single-Player Look Very Messy | first=  Patrick |last= Klepek |date = October 17, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] }}</ref><ref name=\"usgamer history\">{{cite web | url = http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-rise-and-fall-of-visceral-games|  title = The Rise and Fall of Visceral Games | first = Caty | last = McCarthy | date = October 19, 2017 | accessdate = October 20, 2017 | work  = [[US Gamer]] }}</ref> Manveer Heir, who had left EA after finishing his gameplay design work for ''[[Mass Effect Andromeda]]'', acknowledged that the culture within EA was against the development of single-player games, and with Visceral's closure, \"that the linear single-player triple-A game at EA is dead for the time being\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-10-23-manveer-heir-bioware-mass-effect-ea-monetisation | title = \"I've seen people literally spend $15,000 on Mass Effect multiplayer cards\" | first = Robert | last = Purchase | date = October 23, 2017 | accessdate = October 23, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> [[Bethesda Softworks|Bethesda]] in December 7, 2017, decided to collaborate with [[Lynda Carter]] to launch a Public Safety Announcement to save single-player gaming.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/bethesda-kicks-off-a-save-player-1-sale-for-its-single-player-games/ | title = \"Bethesda kicks off a 'Save Player 1' sale for its single-player games\" | first = Andy | last = Chalk | date = December 7, 2017 | accessdate = December 14, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref>\n\n==Game elements==\nAs the narrative and conflict in single-player gameplay is created by a computer rather than a human opponent, single-player games are able to deliver certain gaming experiences that are typically absent - or de-emphasised - in multiplayer games.<ref>\"ThomasDaPsycho.\" : Video Game Story Elements. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref>\n\n===Story===\nSingle-player games rely more heavily on compelling stories to draw the player into the experience and to create a sense of investment. Humans are unpredictable, so human players - allies or enemies - cannot be relied upon to carry a narrative in a particular direction, and so multiplayer games tend not to focus heavily on a linear narrative. By contrast, many single-player games are built around a compelling story.<ref>\"Tales of the Rampant Coyote: What Makes a Great RPG - Mechanics.\" Tales of the Rampant Coyote. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Apr. 2013.</ref>\n\n===Characters===\nWhile a multi-player game relies upon human-human interaction for its conflict, and often for its sense of camaraderie, a single-player game must build these things artificially. As such, single-player games require deeper characterisation of their [[non-player character]]s in order to create connections between the player and the sympathetic characters and to develop deeper antipathy towards the game's [[antagonist|antagonist(s)]]. This is typically true of [[Role-playing video game|role-playing games]] (RPGs), such as ''[[Dragon Quest]]'' and the ''[[Final Fantasy]]'' series, which are primarily character-driven.\n\n===Exceptions===\nThese game elements are not firm, fixed rules; single-player [[Puzzle video game|puzzle games]] such as ''[[Tetris]]'' or [[racing game]]s focus squarely on gameplay.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Massively multiplayer online game]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last1=Fullerton|first1=Tracy|authorlink1=Tracy Fullerton|title=Game Design Workshop: A Playcentric Approach to Creating Innovative Games|date=2014|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=1498785875|edition=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7xjYCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover|accessdate=30 January 2018}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Mitra|first1=Ananda|title=Digital Games: Computers at Play|date=2010|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|isbn=0816067864|pages=24\u201339|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CZrCdZE1WLQC&pg=PA24|accessdate=30 January 2018}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Perron|first1=Bernard|last2=Wolf|first2=Mark J.P.|title=The Routledge Companion to Video Game Studies|date=2014|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=1136290508|pages=253\u2013256|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P43HBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT253|accessdate=30 January 2018}}\n\n{{video game gameplay}}\n\n[[Category:Video game gameplay]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games| ]]\n[[Category:Video game terminology]]\n", "name_user": "125.160.221.176", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-player_video_game"}
{"title_page": "East to Wes", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = East to Wes\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Emily Remler]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1988|5}}\n| recorded   = May 1988\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Penny Lane Studios, New York\n| genre      = [[Jazz]], [[hard bop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=50|s=19}}\n| label      = [[Concord Jazz]]\n| producer   = [[Carl Jefferson|Carl E. Jefferson]]\n| prev_title = [[Together (Larry Coryell and Emily Remler album)|Together]]\n| prev_year  = 1985\n| next_title = This Is Me\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Dryden\">{{cite web|last1=Dryden|first1=Ken|title=East To Wes|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/east-to-wes-mw0000201311|website=AllMusic|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[The Penguin Guide to Jazz]]''\n|rev2Score = {{rating|4|4}}<ref name=\"Penguin\">Richard Cook and Brian Morton, ''The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD'' (Penguin Books Ltd, England, (2004)[1992]: p.1356, {{ISBN|0-141-01416-4}}).</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''East to Wes''''' is a studio album by jazz guitarist [[Emily Remler]]. She was accompanied by pianist [[Hank Jones]], who had played on ''[[Firefly (Emily Remler album)|Firefly]]'' (1981) her first record,  bassist [[Buster Williams]], and drummer [[Marvin Smith|Marvin \"Smitty\" Smith]].\n\nThis recording was Remler's tribute to [[Wes Montgomery]]. For the liner notes, [[Nat Hentoff]] wrote that Remler had said her composition \"East to Wes\" was an \"impression of the earlier bossa nova stuff he did. Wes was one of the greater improvisers I ever heard. His feeling was happy, his soul was beautiful.\"<ref>Nat Hentoff (1988). East To Wes (booklet, page 5). Emily Remler. Concord Records. CCD-4356.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nFor [[Allmusic]] reviewer Ken Dryden this is a highly recommended recording, considering that \"The late guitarist's last CD to be released before her premature death is her finest effort\".<ref name=\"Dryden\" />\n\nIn the 7th edition of the ''[[Penguin Guide to Jazz|Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD]]'', [[Richard Cook (journalist)|Richard Cook]] and [[Brian Morton (Scottish writer)|Brian Morton]] wrote: \"While conceived as a Montgomery homage, Remler's playing actually shows how unlike Wes she really was: harder of tone, her solos more fragmented yet equally lucid.\"<ref name=\"Penguin\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n\n| title1 = Daahoud\n| note1 = [[Clifford Brown]]\n| length1 = 5:16\n\n| title2 = Snowfall\n| note2 = [[Claude Thornhill]]\n| length2 = 6:36\n\n| title3 = [[Hot House (composition)|Hot House]]\n| note3 = [[Tad Dameron]]\n| length3 = 5:41\n\n| title4 = Sweet Georgie Fame\n| note4 = [[Blossom Dearie]] - Sandra Harris\n| length4 = 5:36\n\n| title5 = Ballad for a Music Box\n| note5 = Emily Remler\n| length5 = 7:22\n\n| title6 = Blues for Herb\n| note6 = Emily Remler\n| length6 = 6:24\n\n| title7 = [[Softly, as in a Morning Sunrise]]\n| note7 = [[Sigmund Romberg]] - [[Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n| length7 = 8:11\n\n| title8 = East to Wes\n| note8 = Emily Remler\n| length8 = 6:12\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Emily Remler]] \u2013 [[Gibson ES-330|electric guitar]] (all tracks), [[Ovation Guitar Company|Ovation Adamas acoustic guitar]] (on track#2)\n* [[Hank Jones]] \u2013 [[piano]]\n* [[Buster Williams]] \u2013 [[double bass|bass]]\n* [[Marvin Smith]] \u2013 [[drums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1988 albums]]\n[[Category:Emily Remler albums]]\n[[Category:Female jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Concord Records artists]]\n[[Category:Concord Records albums]]\n[[Category:Bebop guitarists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop guitarists]]\n[[Category:American jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Carl Jefferson]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = East to Wes\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Emily Remler]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1988|5}}\n| recorded   = May 1988\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Penny Lane Studios, New York\n| genre      = [[Jazz]], [[hard bop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=50|s=19}}\n| label      = [[Concord Jazz]]\n| producer   = [[Carl Jefferson|Carl E. Jefferson]]\n| prev_title = [[Together (Larry Coryell and Emily Remler album)|Together]]\n| prev_year  = 1985\n| next_title = This Is Me\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Dryden\">{{cite web|last1=Dryden|first1=Ken|title=East To Wes|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/east-to-wes-mw0000201311|website=AllMusic|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[The Penguin Guide to Jazz]]''\n|rev2Score = {{rating|4|4}}<ref name=\"Penguin\">Richard Cook and Brian Morton, ''The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD'' (Penguin Books Ltd, England, (2004)[1992]: p.1356, {{ISBN|0-141-01416-4}}).</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''East to Wes''''' is a studio album by jazz guitarist [[Emily Remler]]. She was accompanied by pianist [[Hank Jones]], who had played on ''[[Firefly (Emily Remler album)|Firefly]]'' (1981) her first record,  bassist [[Buster Williams]], and drummer [[Marvin Smith|Marvin \"Smitty\" Smith]].\n\nThis recording was Remler's tribute to [[Wes Montgomery]]. For the liner notes, [[Nat Hentoff]] wrote that Remler had said her composition \"East to Wes\" was an \"impression of the earlier bossa nova stuff he did. Wes was one of the greater improvisers I ever heard. His feeling was happy, his soul was beautiful.\"<ref>Nat Hentoff (1988). East To Wes (booklet, page 5). Emily Remler. Concord Records. CCD-4356.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nFor [[Allmusic]] reviewer Ken Dryden this is a highly recommended recording, considering that \"The late guitarist's last CD to be released before her premature death is her finest effort\".<ref name=\"Dryden\" />\n\nIn the 7th edition of the ''[[Penguin Guide to Jazz|Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD]]'', [[Richard Cook (journalist)|Richard Cook]] and [[Brian Morton (Scottish writer)|Brian Morton]] wrote: \"While conceived as a Montgomery homage, Remler's playing actually shows how unlike Wes she really was: harder of tone, her solos more fragmented yet equally lucid.\"<ref name=\"Penguin\">Richard Cook and Brian Morton, ''The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD'' (Penguin Books Ltd, England, (2004)[1992]: p.1356, {{ISBN|0-141-01416-4}}).</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n\n| title1 = Daahoud\n| note1 = [[Clifford Brown]]\n| length1 = 5:16\n\n| title2 = Snowfall\n| note2 = [[Claude Thornhill]]\n| length2 = 6:36\n\n| title3 = [[Hot House (composition)|Hot House]]\n| note3 = [[Tad Dameron]]\n| length3 = 5:41\n\n| title4 = Sweet Georgie Fame\n| note4 = [[Blossom Dearie]] - Sandra Harris\n| length4 = 5:36\n\n| title5 = Ballad for a Music Box\n| note5 = Emily Remler\n| length5 = 7:22\n\n| title6 = Blues for Herb\n| note6 = Emily Remler\n| length6 = 6:24\n\n| title7 = [[Softly, as in a Morning Sunrise]]\n| note7 = [[Sigmund Romberg]] - [[Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n| length7 = 8:11\n\n| title8 = East to Wes\n| note8 = Emily Remler\n| length8 = 6:12\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Emily Remler]] \u2013 [[Gibson ES-330|electric guitar]] (all tracks), [[Ovation Guitar Company|Ovation Adamas acoustic guitar]] (on track#2)\n* [[Hank Jones]] \u2013 [[piano]]\n* [[Buster Williams]] \u2013 [[double bass|bass]]\n* [[Marvin Smith]] \u2013 [[drums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1988 albums]]\n[[Category:Emily Remler albums]]\n[[Category:Female jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Concord Records artists]]\n[[Category:Concord Records albums]]\n[[Category:Bebop guitarists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop guitarists]]\n[[Category:American jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Carl Jefferson]]\n", "name_user": "Urueu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reference updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia